quest_title: 100ml of 10% NaOH is mixed with 100ml of 10% \(\text{H\({}_{2}\)SO\({}_{4}\).}\) The resulting solution is
explanation_txt:
w/v% = \(\cfrac{\text{No. of grams}}{\text{Volume in ml}} \times 100\% = \cfrac{\text{No. of gram equivalents} \times \text{Equivalent Weight}}{\text{Volume in ml}}\)

\(\Rightarrow\) No. of gram equivalents = \(\cfrac{\text{w/v(%)} \times \text{Volume in ml}}{\text{Equivalent weight} \times 100}\)

\(\Rightarrow\) No. of gram equivalents = \(\cfrac{\text{w/v(%)} \times \text{Volume in litre} \times 1000}{\text{Equivalent weight} \times 100}\)

\(\Rightarrow\) No. of gram equivalents = \(\cfrac{\text{w/v(%)} \times \text{Volume in litre} \times 10}{\text{Equivalent weight} \times 100}\)

\(\therefore\) No. of gram equivalents of NaOH = \(\cfrac{10 \times 0.1 \times 10}{40}\) = 0.25

\(\therefore\) No. of gram equivalents of H\(_2\)SO\(_4\) = \(\cfrac{10 \times 0.1 \times 10}{49}\) = 0.204

Since no. of gram equivalents of base is greater than that of acid, the solution will be basic.

The point of intersection is:

\[ 2x - 1 = -\cfrac{x}{2} + \cfrac{3}{2} \]

\[ \Rightarrow \cfrac{5}{2}x = {5}{2} \]

\[ \Rightarrow x = 1 \]

The area is: [see graph]

\[ A = \cfrac{1}{2} \times \sqrt{0.5^2+1} \times \sqrt{1+4} = \cfrac{5}{4} \]

But this line is tangent to circle \( x^2 + y^2 - 2ax = 0 \) whose center is (a,0) and radius is a.

So, by condition of tangency, radius is perpendicular distance of center from the line

\(\begin{array} { l } { \Rightarrow a = \cfrac { a h + 0 - a ^ { 2 } } { \sqrt { h ^ { 2 } + k ^ { 2 } } } } \\ { \Rightarrow h ^ { 2 } + k ^ { 2 } = ( h - a ) ^ { 2 } } \\ { \Rightarrow k ^ { 2 } = a ( a - 2 h ) } \end{array}\)

So, the locus is \( y ^ { 2 } = a ( a - 2 x ) \)
